    "section": "faith-basics",
    "title_zh": "洗礼和圣餐",
    "title_en": "Baptism and Communion",
    "content_zh": "洗礼和圣餐是神给教会的两个「圣礼」——特殊的仪式，用看得见的方式表达看不见的恩典。\n\n洗礼是信仰的公开宣告。当你受洗时，你在众人面前说：\"我相信耶稣，我要跟随祂。\"水代表洗净，浸入水中象征与基督同死，起来象征与基督同复活（罗马书6:4）。洗礼不是得救的条件，而是得救的表达——就像结婚戒指不能让你结婚，但能表明你已婚。\n\n圣餐（或称主餐）是记念耶稣的死。饼代表祂破碎的身体，酒代表祂流出的血。每次吃喝，我们记念祂为我们所做的，也预尝天国的筵席。这不是魔法，而是信心的行动和团契的表达。\n\n这两个圣礼都提醒我们：信仰不只是内心的事，也需要外在的见证。它们是神恩典的可见标志，帮助我们用整个人——包括身体——来敬拜神。",
    "content_en": "Baptism and Communion are the two \"sacraments\" God gave the church — special ceremonies that express invisible grace in visible ways.\n\nBaptism is a public declaration of faith. When you're baptized, you're telling everyone: \"I believe in Jesus and I'm following Him.\" Water represents cleansing, going under symbolizes dying with Christ, coming up symbolizes rising with Christ (Romans 6:4). Baptism isn't a requirement for salvation but an expression of it — like a wedding ring doesn't make you married, but shows you are.\n\nCommunion (or Lord's Supper) remembers Jesus' death. The bread represents His broken body, the wine His shed blood. Every time we eat and drink, we remember what He did for us and get a foretaste of heaven's feast. It's not magic, but an act of faith and expression of fellowship.\n\nBoth sacraments remind us: faith isn't just internal, it needs external witness. They're visible signs of God's grace, helping us worship God with our whole person — including our bodies.",
